// di-snapsend — replicate immediately after a successful apt transaction.
//
// Fires AFTER snapper's post snapshot (80snapper) so the replicated state is the
// consistent post-change @, including any kernel/grub/initramfs updates written by
// package postinst scripts. This pairs the live /boot + /boot/efi rsync tier with the
// matching snapshot, closing the timer's randomized-offset skew window for the case that
// matters (apt-driven OS/boot changes).
//
// --no-block: don't make apt wait for the (possibly minutes-long) btrfs send.
// start (not the script): reuse snapsend.service so the engine's flock, logging, and
//   resource limits apply. A collision with an in-flight run is a clean no-op (the engine
//   takes a non-blocking flock and exits via _AlreadyRunning).
// || true: a queued/failed service start must never fail the apt transaction.
DPkg::Post-Invoke-Success { "if [ -x /usr/bin/systemctl ] || [ -x /bin/systemctl ]; then systemctl --no-block start snapsend.service || true; fi"; };
